<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=9806984233900></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9806984233900><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=9806984233900>RE: What makes a good Puller? (NT)</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=9806984233900#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=492><span id=Sage>Gorthin</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>153 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Jan 28th 4:16 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>What makes a good puller?&nbsp;&nbsp;Situational awareness.  Sounds simple enough, but it has a lot to it.<br><br>Knowing the pathing of the monsters you pull.  The aggro radius of things you do not want pulled.  Knowing when the backspawn is going to happen.  Knowing the general mana level of the casters without asking.  Knowing whether when you pull this, if a wanderer comes along, will the group be alright?  Knowing whether the mob is worth the effort to kill, if you do not need to pull it. Knowing the general difficulty of the mobs you will be facing.  i.e. are they casters?  Do the proc a strong poison?  Do they gate?  Summon?  Quad for 220 each hit?  etc etc.<br><br>Being willing to eat a death on a bad pull if FD doesn't come through for you.  I can't tell you how many times I have seen people train their group just because they wanted a chance to live, instead of eating a death in an easy spot to recover a corpse.  Yes, it sucks when you lose xp.  But it sucks worse when you cause everyone else to lose xp, and then they boot you because you "Sux0r".<br><br>On the materiallistic side:  Knowing if this mob is a PH for a "phat lewtz" mob.  Knowing if the mob has the opportunity to carry "phat lewtz".  Knowing whether the mob carries your class's "phat lewtz" hehe.<br><br>Perhaps the  most important thing is being able to pace your group.  Keeping everyone busy without hearing OOM every 5 seconds.  Staying busy, but letting the casters keep enough mana for that "Oh #$@$!" situation where you will at least have the opportunity to make it out alive.  And like I said above, knowing when to eat a death on a bad, or unlucky, pull.<br><br>A good puller learns through observation, hearing from others, and personal experience.  It is not something that can be squeezed down into one or two things.  If you can, the best thing to do is watch someone else pull by following them a LITTLE from your group, and watch how they pull back to you.  I mean, do not follow them all the way to the mob, just watch from a distance.  And above all else, ask nicely.  Most people are &gt;more&lt; than willing to share how to pull.  All it takes is a polite, complete sentence.  If they are not busy, they will more than likely give you some insight.<br><br>Gorthin Spiritcaller<br>51 Shaman BB<br>Drindal 35 Monk BB<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
