<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=98052529517552></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98052529517552><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=98052529517552>RE: Starting a monk...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=98052529517552#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=4986><span id=Scholar>Alerithon</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>92 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Jan 26th 4:11 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.33]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I think it's a wash between maxing str or agi.&nbsp;&nbsp;The extra ATT will mean you do maximum damage more often, and hit more often, while the higher AGI will add some AC and reduce damage you take, but more importantly, allow you to dodge and block more often.  At level 27 I shrug off hits for 50, because I know that I'm going to dodge or block the next three 50 hits.  <br><br>Either way, there are enough good str and agi boosting jewelry that you'll be able to customize and compensate for whichever stat is lower.  Not many combined str/agi pieces, but there are many str/dex and agi/dex.  High dex is going to help at higher levels as you get access to proc. weapons.<br><br>My personal view is, as a monk, you're dealing damage OVER TIME.  Getting that extra 1 or 2 points of damage that a high str might convey isn't as important as staying in the fight longer, and high agi helps you do that.<br>&nbsp;<br>Alerithon Tigerspirit<br>29 rank monk, E'Ci<br>Avatara</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
